			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Mine finally died yesterday. It was an Archos 6000, original model. I've jerryrigged it and kept it working for nearly five years; good return on a $200 investment. It was infinitely preferable to any CD or tape player I've ever used. It is time to get a new one.
<br />

<br />
What I'd prefer...
<br />
<ul><li>Uses standard, replaceable, rechargeable batteries (AAA, AA, whatever, just nothing proprietary.)
<br />
<li>USB2 and/or Firewire interface.
<br />
<li>Unit can draw power from USB2/Firewire; does not need AC adapter to jack in to a computer.
<br />
<li>Capacity in the 10GB range for a flash player, or 20GB-80GB for a disk-based unit.
<br />
<li>If possible, uses standard flash or disk technology, so the storage device can be replaced after failure.
<br />
<li>Greater than a one year warranty.
<br />
<li>Plays all formats, including MP3 and OGG.
<br />
<li>Is not DRM-restricted.
<br />
<li>Can be used as a disk drive on a PC for transferring files.
<br />
<li>Battery life greater than five hours on a full charge.
<br />
<li>Enough volume output to hurt my ears on a set of good headphones.
<br />
<li>Size and weight are not an issue. Anything portable is fine.</ul>What are folks using now? Does anyone know any players that sport this feature set? Price is not a concern; I can happily drop $1000 on this if necessary. I'd rather not, though. I'm also not interested in an iPod. They have a great interface, but are far too restrictive and proprietary for my tastes. I haven't done much research yet; the market has opened up considerably from where it was when the original Archos came out. Once I start digging into it I'll post my findings here as well.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by EvilNight on Thu Mar 10, 2005 11:37 pm; edited 2 times in total</span><br />
