			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				First glances seem to indicate the big two are the Creative Nomad Zen Xtra and the iRiver H340.
<br />

<br />
Pros of the Zen<ul><li>Standard 2.5mm laptop hard drive (not smaller, more expensive 1.5 or 1.8 models).
<br />
<li>Proprietary, but removeable battery.
<br />
<li>Excellent price per megabyte.</ul>Cons of the Zen<ul><li><span style="font-weight: bold">Requires</span> proprietary software; does not work as a standard USB drive. Uses its own non-standard file system.
<br />
<li>Does not draw power from USB, requires AC adapter.
<br />
<li>Limited file type support. (MP3, WMA, WAV only)</ul>I can't really use a player with a proprietary file system. That's simply stupid.
<br />

<br />
Pros of the iRiver 340<ul><li>Standard USB2 drive with FAT32 file system. No proprietary software required.
<br />
<li>Draws power and recharges from USB, no AC adapter required.
<br />
<li>Supports nearly all file types imaginable; way beyond the call of duty on this one.
<br />
<li>18-25hr battery life on maximum volume output (that's out-freaking-standing).
<br />
<li>The unmatched <a href="http://www.rockbox.org/twiki/bin/view/Main/IriverPort" target="_blank" class="postlink">Rockbox</a> firmware developed for the Archos is being ported to the iRiver. Big, big bonus; Rockbox is open source and <a href="http://www.rockbox.org/twiki/bin/view/Main/FeatureComparison" target="_blank" class="postlink">light years ahead</a> of any commercial mp3 player firmware.</ul>Cons of the iRiver 340<ul><li>Proprietary, internal battery; can only be changed by opening the case and soldering. Major turnoff.
<br />
<li>Uses the smaller 1.8mm hard drive model; considerably more expensive to replace, but still standard.
<br />
<li>Considerably more expensive player.<li>There appears to be a one to three minute boot time depending on the quantity of music loaded. Again, major pita. A Rockbox-based firmware would not have this problem, however.</ul>I'm leaning towards an iRivier for now. Need to keep digging up information later.
<br />

<br />
The PSP looks <a href="http://www.engadget.com/entry/1234000510024287/" target="_blank" class="postlink">pretty awesome,</a> but 1.8GB is a bit too small for my MP3 collection. I'm planning to use the MP3 player as a portable hard drive for transferring large quantities of files (think 20GB/week or so) between home, work, and other places. If I were thinking of a flash player, though, the PSP would be a no brainer for sure.
<br />

<br />
The reason I'm not big on the iPod is that changing out defective parts is a bitch, and I despise iTunes and their file management system. It also requiers apple proprietary software to get data in and out, I believe. It's hella expensive, even compared to the iRiver.<br />
