				<div class="postbody">
				I do not own any of those but after doing my research I have determined that when I get the funds I want a Creative Zen Micro.  It seems to offer the best bang for the buck.  For various reasons, probably the same as you, I want to stay the hell away from iPod.
<br />

<br />
I decided I want a Creative because:
<br />

<br />
A)  It's not Apple
<br />
B)  Allegedly the sound quality is much better than an iPod
<br />
C)  Replaceable Battery
<br />
D)  It's not Apple
<br />
E)  I like how it looks, I must be in the minority but I find the iPod too sterile looking.
<br />
F)  FM Radio
<br />
G)  It's not Apple
<br />

<br />
According to the Creative website the Zen Micro has the ability: 
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Removable Disk
<br />
Store and transfer not only your favorite tunes, but important data files as well. Zen Micro's Removable Disk mode lets you connect your player to the computer and directly copy the files you need. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
My understand is that if you want to transport files then you can do a simple drag and drop.  To add music files to your playlist you may need their software, though.
<br />

<br />
I would really like to find a player that supported OGG and FLAC formats as well as an AM reciever.  That, though, does not exist.<br />
