			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=109347&amp;sid=99f48ad74f8fc2835a1b1600c8ab08c3#109347"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Fri Mar 11, 2005 2:36 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Favorite brand of portable hardware MP3/media player?</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=109347&amp;sid=99f48ad74f8fc2835a1b1600c8ab08c3"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Actually, according to the FAQ on the Zen Xtra, you can't just drag and drop the files. Any PC you expect to be able to use read the disk has to have the proprietary Zen software loaded for that to work. That's one of my pet peeves, especially since the Zen software is windows-only. Creative has apparently extended a big @#%$-you towards anyone suggesting they open up their player software, and that is not a sensible business strategy so I'm a bit confused at their intentions.
<br />

<br />
The <a href="http://www.iriveramerica.com/prod/hd/h340.aspx" target="_blank" class="postlink">iRiver H340</a> has an FM tuner (no AM, unfortunately), and supports OGG files. It doesn't support FLAC format, however, if Rockbox is ported to it (only a matter of time, really), it will then be able to play FLAC files. It also doesn't require any proprietary software, it's a simple FAT32 formatted disk.
<br />

<br />
Both of those players have thriving user communities. There is no place better than a community message board to learn about all the quirks and hassles of a player. They've got the kinds of FAQs the companies would rather you didn't see, as well as all kinds of hacks, tricks, warnings, solutions to common problems, etc.
<br />

<br />
The <a href="http://www.iriveramerica.com/prod/hd/h340.aspx" target="_blank" class="postlink">iRiver 340</a> forums: <a href="http://www.misticriver.net/boards/" target="_blank">http://www.misticriver.net/boards/</a>
<br />

<br />
The <a href="http://www.nomadworld.com/products/Jukebox_ZenXtra/features.asp" target="_blank" class="postlink">Nomad Zen Xtra</a> forums: <a href="http://www.nomadness.net/modules.php?name=Forums" target="_blank">http://www.nomadness.net/modules.php?name=Forums</a>
<br />

<br />
Basically I'm stuck choosing between proprietary HD formats and hardwired batteries. That's what it comes down to. I've really got no qualms about cracking one of these open... they are brain dead simple inside, replacing the batteries and hard disks is easy. I'd replaced my Archos player's 2.5" hard disk three times. 
<br />

<br />
I also noticed the Creative products have a meager 30-day warranty, while the iRiver products have a one year warranty. That's another point in iRiver's favor, especially since flashing/tampering with iRiver's firmware does not, by the company's own statements, void your warranty.<br />
